Project Title
SecureFusion: A Privacy-Preserving Distributed Salary Survey Using Secure Multi-Party Computation
________________________________________
2. Objective & Problem Statement
The "Why"
In modern organizations, salary information is considered highly sensitive and confidential. Although management often needs to calculate the total salary expenditure and average salary across departments, revealing each department’s salary information may violate privacy requirements and organizational policies.
Traditional centralized approaches require all departments to submit their salary data to a central server. This creates several challenges:
•	Exposure of sensitive salary information.
•	Increased risk of insider threats and data leakage.
•	Single point of failure in centralized systems.
•	Lack of privacy preservation during data aggregation.
To address these challenges, this project proposes a distributed privacy-preserving salary survey system using Secure Multi-Party Computation (SMPC).
The system enables multiple departments to collaboratively calculate the global salary sum and global average salary without revealing their individual salary totals to any other department or to a centralized database server.
The project demonstrates how privacy-preserving computation can be integrated into distributed database environments while maintaining data confidentiality.
________________________________________
Core Logic
The project implements the Secure Sum Protocol, a fundamental Secure Multi-Party Computation technique.
Assume there are four departments:
•	Site A
•	Site B
•	Site C
•	Site D
Each department stores a private salary total:
•	SA
•	SB
•	SC
•	SD
The objective is to calculate:
GlobalSum = SA + SB + SC + SD
without exposing any individual salary value.
Protocol Steps
Step 1: Random Mask Generation
Site A generates a secret random number:
R
This value is known only to Site A.
________________________________________
Step 2: Data Masking
Site A computes:
M1 = SA + R
and sends M1 to Site B.
________________________________________
Step 3: Site B Aggregation
Site B adds its private salary:
M2 = M1 + SB
and forwards M2 to Site C.
________________________________________
Step 4: Site C Aggregation
Site C computes:
M3 = M2 + SC
and sends M3 to Site D.
________________________________________
Step 5: Site D Aggregation
Site D computes:
M4 = M3 + SD
and sends M4 back to Site A.
________________________________________
Step 6: Final Decryption
Site A removes the random mask:
GlobalSum = M4 − R
The global average salary is then calculated as:
GlobalAverage = GlobalSum / 4
________________________________________
Privacy Preservation
At no point does any department receive another department’s private salary value.
The transmitted values are only intermediate aggregated results, which do not reveal the original salary totals.
Therefore:
•	Site A cannot determine SB, SC, or SD.
•	Site B cannot determine SA, SC, or SD.
•	Site C cannot determine SA, SB, or SD.
•	Site D cannot determine SA, SB, or SC.
This preserves privacy while still enabling collaborative computation.
________________________________________
Mathematical Correctness
Let:
M1 = SA + R
M2 = SA + R + SB
M3 = SA + R + SB + SC
M4 = SA + R + SB + SC + SD
Site A computes:
GlobalSum = M4 − R
Substituting M4:
GlobalSum
= (SA + R + SB + SC + SD) − R
= SA + SB + SC + SD
Thus:
Σ(Private Data) = Global Sum
which proves the correctness of the Secure Sum protocol while maintaining privacy.
3. Dataset Specification
Source
Simulated Dataset
The dataset is manually generated for educational and experimental purposes. No external dataset is required because the project focuses on privacy-preserving distributed computation rather than large-scale data analytics.
________________________________________
Size
The system consists of 4 independent JSON files, each representing a separate department (site).
Site	Department	Storage File
Site A	IT	salary.json
Site B	HR	salary.json
Site C	Finance	salary.json
Site D	Marketing	salary.json
Total Records: 4
________________________________________
Schema
Each site stores its own private salary information using the following JSON structure:
{
    "department": "IT",
    "salary_total": 120000
}
Attributes
Attribute	Data Type	Description
department	String	Department name
salary_total	Integer	Total salary budget of the department
________________________________________
Fragmentation Strategy
This project applies Horizontal Fragmentation by Department.
Each department owns and manages its salary data independently.
The fragmentation layout is:
Site	Data Ownership
Site A	IT Department Salary
Site B	HR Department Salary
Site C	Finance Department Salary
Site D	Marketing Department Salary
No site has direct access to another site's private salary data.
Instead of transferring raw data, sites exchange only intermediate Secure Sum values generated by the protocol.
This fragmentation strategy reflects a common distributed database scenario where data is physically distributed across multiple locations while computation is performed collaboratively.
________________________________________
4. System Architecture
Nodes
The system simulates four distributed database sites running as independent Node.js processes on localhost.
Site	Department	Port
Site A	IT	3001
Site B	HR	3002
Site C	Finance	3003
Site D	Marketing	3004
Each site operates independently and maintains its own local storage.
________________________________________
Communication Layer
Communication between sites is implemented using:
•	HTTP REST API
•	Express.js
•	Axios
The Secure Sum protocol follows a circular communication topology:
Site A
   |
   v
Site B
   |
   v
Site C
   |
   v
Site D
   |
   v
Site A
Communication flow:
1.	Site A generates a random masking value R.
2.	Site A sends the masked salary sum to Site B.
3.	Site B adds its salary and forwards the result to Site C.
4.	Site C adds its salary and forwards the result to Site D.
5.	Site D adds its salary and returns the result to Site A.
6.	Site A removes R and calculates the final Global Sum and Global Average.
________________________________________
Storage
Each site stores data locally using JSON files.
Storage structure:
Distributed-SMPC-Salary-Survey
│
├── site-a
│   └── data
│       └── salary.json
│
├── site-b
│   └── data
│       └── salary.json
│
├── site-c
│   └── data
│       └── salary.json
│
├── site-d
│   └── data
│       └── salary.json
This design ensures that salary information remains physically distributed and privately managed by each department.
No centralized database server is used during computation.
________________________________________
Architectural Characteristics
The proposed architecture demonstrates several distributed database concepts:
•	Data Distribution: Data is stored across multiple independent sites.
•	Local Autonomy: Each site controls its own dataset.
•	Distributed Processing: Computation is performed collaboratively across sites.
•	Privacy Preservation: Raw salary values are never shared.
•	Fault Isolation: Each site can operate independently as a separate process.
The architecture effectively simulates a distributed environment while remaining lightweight enough to run on a single machine using multiple localhost services.
5. Tech Stack & Implementation Plan
Programming Language
Node.js (JavaScript)
Node.js is selected because it provides lightweight asynchronous communication, rapid REST API development, and is highly suitable for simulating distributed systems through multiple independent processes.
________________________________________
Deployment Environment
Localhost-based Distributed Simulation
The system will be deployed as four independent Node.js processes running on different ports:
•	Site A → Port 3001
•	Site B → Port 3002
•	Site C → Port 3003
•	Site D → Port 3004
Although executed on a single machine, each site behaves as an independent distributed node.
________________________________________
Libraries and Frameworks
Express.js
Purpose:
•	Build REST APIs
•	Handle incoming requests
•	Implement Secure Sum communication endpoints
Example Endpoints:
GET  /salary
GET  /start-secure-sum
POST /secure-sum
POST /final-result
________________________________________
Axios
Purpose:
•	Enable communication between distributed sites.
•	Forward intermediate Secure Sum values between nodes.
Example:
Site A → Site B
Site B → Site C
Site C → Site D
Site D → Site A
________________________________________
File System (fs)
Purpose:
•	Read local JSON datasets.
•	Simulate private departmental databases.
